  urldate = {2026-05-15},
  abstract = {This essay examines why authoritarian regimes are increasingly relying on subtle forms of digital censorship rather than outright information denial. Focusing on China’s Great Firewall and Russia’s RuNet, it argues that tactics such as friction and flooding allow governments to suppress dissent more effectively by minimizing public backlash while also undermining collective action. In contrast to visible bans or blackouts, these quieter methods preserve a façade of openness, making censorship harder for citizens to detect and therefore less likely to provoke resistance. The essay shows how both China and Russia use selective filtering, throttling, distraction, and information manipulation to weaken opposition movements without fully closing off the internet. Together, these cases demonstrate that “quiet control” has become a sustainable strategy of digital authoritarianism in the modern age.},
